The '''Levenson Self-Report Psychopathy Scale''' is a test of [[psychopathy]] for research situations. It was developed by Michael R. Levenson in 1995.<ref>{{cite journal | author = Gaughan J. D. Miller E. T., Pryor L. R. | date = Dec 2008 | title = The Levenson Self-Report Psychopathy Scale:An Examination of the Personality Traits and Disorders Associated With the LSRP Factors | url = http://asm.sagepub.com/content/15/4/450.short?rss=1&ssource=mfr | journal = Assessment | volume = 15 | issue = 4| pages = 450–63 }}</ref><ref>Walters, Glenn; Brinkley, Chad; Magaletta, Philip; Diamond, Pamela (2008). [http://www.mendeley.com/research/taxometric-analysis-levenson-selfreport-psychopathy-scale/ "Taxometric analysis of the Levenson Self-Report Psychopathy scale".] Journal of Personality Assessment.</ref><ref>Martin Sellbom. [https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/20953972 "Elaborating on the construct validity of the Levenson self-report psychopathy scale in incarcerated and non-incarcerated samples".]</ref> 

