'''Medical integration environment''' (MIE) are specialised tools designed to simplify the sharing of medical and related data between medical equipment and electronic health records.  Technically, they are similar to an [[Enterprise Service Bus]] but with several extra features allowing for legacy systems that do not use web services messaging. Typically, they use [[Java Message Service]]; most [[Enterprise Application Integration]] systems can be modified to be used as an MIE but may lack the crucial [[HL7]] and [[Arden syntax]] for storing medical knowledge.

[[Category:Health informatics]]

An '''ophthalmotrope''' (from the [[Ancient Greek language|Greek]] roots ὀφθαλμοῦ, ''ophthalmos'', i.e. eye and -τροπή, -''tropē'', i.e. turning) is an apparatus for demonstrating the [[Eye movement (sensory)|movements of the eye]] and the action of the different [[Extraocular muscles|muscles]] which produce them, consisting essentially of a model eyeball to which are attached strings and pulleys to duplicate the line force of the muscles. Movements of the eye are [[Kinematics|kinematically]] complex and can be described as a combination of rotations about changing rotation centers. But even when ocular mechanics are simplified to pure rotations about a head-fixed rotation center, their noncommutative property makes them difficult to visualize. [[Christian Georg Theodor Ruete|Ruete]], [[Johann Benedict Listing|Listing]], [[Franciscus Donders|Donders]], [[Hermann von Helmholtz|Helmholtz]], [[Albrecht von Graefe|von Graefe]], [[Alfred Wilhelm Volkmann|Volkmann]] and many others have provided the broad outline of an answer to the question how the eye rotates during [[Eye movement (sensory)|eye movements]].
== History == [[File:Ruete's Ophthalmotrope 2nd model, 1857.jpg|thumb|Ruete's Ophthalmotrope 2nd model, 1857]] Historically, mechanical representations of oculomotor mechanics have been used for visualization of eye movements and their interaction with visual geometry. Many mechanical models of eye movements have been constructed and studied in the nineteenth century.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Simonsz|first=H. J.|author2=den Tonkelaar, I.|title=19th century mechanical models of eye movements, Donders' law, Listing's law and Helmholtz' direction circles|journal=Doc Ophthalmol|year=1990|volume=74|issue=1–2|pages=95–112|url=http://repub.eur.nl/res/pub/40457/10.1007_BF00165667.pdf|doi=10.1007/BF00165667|pmid=2209371}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=den Tonkelaar|first1=I.|last2=Henkes|first2=G. K. |last3=van Leersum| title=Eye and instruments. Nineteenth-century ophthalmological instruments in the Netherlands|year=1996|publisher=Batavian Lion|location=Amsterdam|pages=175–186}}</ref> The first ophthalmotrope was made by [[Christian Georg Theodor Ruete]] in 1845 <ref>{{cite book|last=Ruete|first=Christian Georg Theodor|title=Das Ophthalmotrop, dessen Bau und Gebrauch. Göttinger Studien|year=1845|publisher=Vandenhoeck und Ruprecht|location=Göttingen|url=https://archive.org/details/dasophthalmotrop00ruet}}</ref> and it was he who gave it the name “ophthalmotrope”. Ruete's first version ophthalmotrope had the eye mounted in nested gimbals, and his second model,<ref>{{cite book|last=Ruete|first=Christian Georg Theodor|title=Ein neues Ophthalmotrop, zur Erläuterung der Functionen der Muskeln und brechenden Medien des menschlichen Auges|year=1857|publisher=Druck und Verlag von B. G. Teubner|location=Leipzig|url=https://archive.org/details/einneuesophthalm00ruet}}</ref> which emulated [[Listing's law]], mounted the rotation axis in a rotatable ring. Ruete’s second model of 1857 was an altogether more sophisticated model that demonstrates both the movements of the eye and, importantly, the action of the ocular muscles. Both Donders’s and Listing’s laws can be demonstrated on this model. The degree of muscle contraction or extension can be measured on a scale at the back of the model. Other ophthalmotropes were designed lather by [[Edmund Landolt|Landolt]], [[Hermann Jakob Knapp|Knapp]], [[Franciscus Donders|Donders]], [[Hermann Snellen|Snellen]], [[Wilhelm Wundt|Wundt]], and others. Recently, Schreiber and Schor <ref>{{cite journal|last=Schreiber|first=K. M.|author2=Schor, C. M.|title=A virtual ophthalmotrope illustrating oculomotor coordinate systems and retinal projection geometry|journal=Journal of Vision|year=2007|volume=7|issue=10|pages=4 1–14|doi=10.1167/7.10.4|url=http://www.journalofvision.org/content/7/10/4.long#xref-ref-22-1|pmid=17997673}}</ref> have published a modern software version of ophthalmotrope. They presented a virtual gimbaled model of the oculomotor system, which provides accurate visualization of the kinematics of the three major oculomotor coordinate systems and qualitative estimates of the effects of the different coordinate systems on ocular torsion. The virtual ophthalmotrope presented by Schreiber and Schor is a modification and extension of Donders' design,<ref>{{cite journal|last=Donders|first=F.C.|title=Die Bewegungen des Auges, veranschaulicht durch das Phaenophthalmotrop|journal=Archiv für Ophthalmologie|year=1870|volume=16|pages=154–175}}</ref> by adding Listing's extended law and displacement plane geometry to its basic visualization capabilities.
